replies.comment info:
@Tony 

I like your headline.  I does feel as if we have been on a Covid Rollercoaster.  

I would like to draw your attention to the right side of the graph.  Why do you think that there was an increase in hospitalizations during September?

@Kayla 

Hi Kayla,

You have an interesting wonder about the relationship between infection and hospitalization.  But these graphs aren’t comparing raw numbers.  Rather they are comparing the rate of infection per 100,000 people.  Why do you think it was done this way?

@Abby Murnane 

Hello Abby,

Kudos for noticing that these graphs are about hospitalization rates and not raw numbers!  Did you notice that the rates started increasing mid-summer?  What change in the virus might account for this?  It’s also great that you noticed that overall, children under 18 are hospitalized at lower rates than adults.  But these graphs are meant to be compared between as well as within.  How do the rates compare adult-to-child for the two groups of states?

@Sophia K 

Hello Sophia,

Do you think that one way to increase vaccination rates might be to highlight (as done in this graph) the hospitalization rates for those under 18 who are not yet eligible for the vaccine?  What other things could be done that might influence an increase in vaccination rates?

@Ethan J. 

Hello Ethan,

Note that this graph is about hospitalization rates, not the number of shots people are taking :)

@Gavin

Hello Gavin,

This graph is about hospitalization rates for two age groups in two groups of states.  It helps us compare those groups with respect to those rates.  How does it tell you that there are more unvaccinated adults than vaccinated?

@L. D. 

Hi L. D.

I wonder if there might be factors other than the conservative lifestyles you cite that may influence whether a person is vaccine hesitant.  What do those southern states—particularly Alabama, Georgia, Mississippi, and Louisiana—have in common that contribute to lower vaccination rates?  Note that this information is not included in the graphs themselves.  We have to seek it out through other means!

@Aneja 

Hello Aneja,

What change in the COVID-19 virus occurred starting in May that might answer your question about why the hospitalization rate increased so much in this time period?

@Jeffrey 

Greetings fellow Arizonan :)

Your “wonder” question about the adult hospitalizations is spot on!  The category of adults is indeed a wide one.  Why do you think this graph just compares the wider group of adults to the narrower group of those under 18, especially through the beginning of September?

